# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carbon-nanotubes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Carbon is capable of forming many allotropes (structurally different forms of the same element) due to its valency (tetravalent).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Well-known forms of carbon include diamond and graphite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] In recent decades, many more allotropes have been discovered and researched, including ball shapes such as buckminsterfullerene and sheets such as graphene.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Larger-scale structures of carbon include nanotubes, nanobuds carbon quantum dots and nanoribbons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Other unusual forms of carbon exist at very high temperatures or extreme pressures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Around 500 hypothetical 3‑periodic allotropes of carbon are known as of 2016, according to the Samara Carbon Allotrope Database (SACADA).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Under certain conditions, carbon can be found in its atomic form.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It can be formed by vaporizing graphite, by passing large electric currents to form a carbon arc under very low pressure.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It is extremely reactive, but it is an intermediate product used in the creation of carbenes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Diatomic carbon can also be found under certain conditions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It is often detected via spectroscopy in extraterrestrial bodies, including comets and certain stars.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The crystal structure of diamond is a face-centered cubic lattice having eight atoms per unit cell to form a diamond cubic structure.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Each carbon atom is covalently bonded to four other carbons in a tetrahedral geometry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] These tetrahedrons together form a 3-dimensional network of six-membered carbon rings in the chair conformation, allowing for zero bond angle strain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The bonding occurs through sp3 hybridized orbitals to give a C-C bond length of 154 pm.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] This network of unstrained covalent bonds makes diamond extremely strong.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Diamond is thermodynamically less stable than graphite at pressures below 1.7 GPa.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The dominant industrial use of diamond is cutting, drilling (drill bits), grinding (diamond edged cutters), and polishing.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Most uses of diamonds in these technologies do not require large diamonds, and most diamonds that are not gem-quality can find an industrial use.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Diamonds are embedded in drill tips and saw blades or ground into a powder for use in grinding and polishing applications (due to its extraordinary hardness).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Specialized applications include use in laboratories as containment for high pressure experiments (see diamond anvil), high-performance bearings, and specialized windows of technical apparatuses.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The market for industrial-grade diamonds operates much differently from its gem-grade counterpart.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Industrial diamonds are valued mostly for their hardness and heat conductivity, making many of the gemological characteristics of diamond, including clarity and color, mostly irrelevant.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] This helps explain why 80% of mined diamonds (equal to about 100 million carats or 20 tonnes annually) are unsuitable for use as gemstones and known as *bort*, destined for industrial use.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] With the continuing advances being made in the production of synthetic diamond, future applications are beginning to become feasible.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Garnering much excitement is the possible use of diamond as a semiconductor suitable to build microchips from, or the use of diamond as a heat sink in electronics.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Significant research efforts in Japan, Europe, and the United States are under way to capitalize on the potential offered by diamond's unique material properties, combined with increased quality and quantity of supply starting to become available from synthetic diamond manufacturers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Graphite conducts electricity, due to delocalization of the pi bond electrons above and below the planes of the carbon atoms.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] These electrons are free to move, so are able to conduct electricity.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] However, the electricity is only conducted along the plane of the layers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] In diamond, all four outer electrons of each carbon atom are 'localized' between the atoms in covalent bonding.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The movement of electrons is restricted and diamond does not conduct an electric current.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] In graphite, each carbon atom uses only 3 of its 4 outer energy level electrons in covalently bonding to three other carbon atoms in a plane.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Each carbon atom contributes one electron to a delocalized system of electrons that is also a part of the chemical bonding.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The delocalized electrons are free to move throughout the plane.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] For this reason, graphite conducts electricity along the planes of carbon atoms, but does not conduct electricity in a direction at right angles to the plane.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Graphite powder is used as a dry lubricant.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Although it might be thought that this industrially important property is due entirely to the loose interlamellar coupling between sheets in the structure, in fact in a vacuum environment (such as in technologies for use in space), graphite was found to be a very poor lubricant.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] This fact led to the discovery that graphite's lubricity is due to adsorbed air and water between the layers, unlike other layered dry lubricants such as molybdenum disulfide.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Recent studies suggest that an effect called superlubricity can also account for this effect.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] When a large number of crystallographic defects (physical) bind these planes together, graphite loses its lubrication properties and becomes pyrolytic carbon, a useful material in blood-contacting implants such as prosthetic heart valves.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Graphite is the most stable allotrope of carbon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Contrary to popular belief, high-purity graphite does not readily burn, even at elevated temperatures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] For this reason, it is used in nuclear reactors and for high-temperature crucibles for melting metals.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] At very high temperatures and pressures (roughly 2000 °C and 5 GPa), it can be transformed into diamond.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Natural and crystalline graphites are not often used in pure form as structural materials due to their shear-planes, brittleness and inconsistent mechanical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] In its pure glassy (isotropic) synthetic forms, pyrolytic graphite and carbon fiber graphite are extremely strong, heat-resistant (to 3000 °C) materials, used in reentry shields for missile nosecones, solid rocket engines, high temperature reactors, brake shoes and electric motor brushes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Intumescent or expandable graphites are used in fire seals, fitted around the perimeter of a fire door.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] During a fire the graphite intumesces (expands and chars) to resist fire penetration and prevent the spread of fumes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] A typical *start expansion temperature* (SET) is between 150 and 300 °C.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Graphite's specific gravity is 2.3, which makes it less dense than diamond.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Graphite is slightly more reactive than diamond.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] This is because the reactants are able to penetrate between the hexagonal layers of carbon atoms in graphite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It is unaffected by ordinary solvents, dilute acids, or fused alkalis.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] However, chromic acid oxidizes it to carbon dioxide.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] A single layer of graphite is called graphene and has extraordinary electrical, thermal, and physical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It can be produced by epitaxy on an insulating or conducting substrate or by mechanical exfoliation (repeated peeling) from graphite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Its applications may include replacing silicon in high-performance electronic devices.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] With two layers stacked, bilayer graphene results with different properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Lonsdaleite is an allotrope sometimes called "hexagonal diamond", formed from graphite present in meteorites upon their impact on the earth.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The great heat and pressure of the impact transforms the graphite into a denser form similar to diamond but retaining graphite's hexagonal crystal lattice.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] "Hexagonal diamond" has also been synthesized in the laboratory, by compressing and heating graphite either in a static press or using explosives.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It can also be produced by the thermal decomposition of a polymer, poly(hydridocarbyne), at atmospheric pressure, under inert gas atmosphere (e.g. argon, nitrogen), starting at temperature 110 °C (230 °F).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Graphenylene is a single layer carbon material with biphenylene-like subunits as basis in its hexagonal lattice structure.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Carbophene is a 2 dimensional covalent organic framework.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] 4-6 carbophene has been synthesized from 1-3-5 trihydroxybenzene.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It consists of 4-carbon and 6-carbon rings in 1:1 ratio.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The angles between the three σ-bonds of the orbitals are approximately 120°, 90°, and 150°.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] AA'-graphite is an allotrope of carbon similar to graphite, but where the layers are positioned differently to each other as compared to the order in graphite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It can be made via high pressures, but without that pressure, the material reverts to graphene.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Another technique is to add hydrogen atoms, but those bonds are weak.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Using fluorine (xenon-difluoride) instead brings the layers closer together, strengthening the bonds.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Coal and soot or carbon black are informally called amorphous carbon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] However, they are products of pyrolysis (the process of decomposing a substance by the action of heat), which does not produce true amorphous carbon under normal conditions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The *buckminsterfullerenes*, or usually just *fullerenes* or *buckyballs* for short, were discovered in 1985 by a team of scientists from Rice University and the University of Sussex, three of whom were awarded the 1996 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] They are named for the resemblance to the geodesic structures devised by Richard Buckminster "Bucky" Fuller.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Fullerenes are positively curved molecules of varying sizes composed entirely of carbon, which take the form of a hollow sphere, ellipsoid, or tube (the C60 version has the same form as a traditional stitched soccer ball).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] As of the early twenty-first century, the chemical and physical properties of fullerenes are still under heavy study, in both pure and applied research labs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] In April 2003, fullerenes were under study for potential medicinal use — binding specific antibiotics to the structure to target resistant bacteria and even target certain cancer cells such as melanoma.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Carbon nanotubes, also called buckytubes, are cylindrical carbon molecules with novel properties that make them potentially useful in a wide variety of applications (e.g., nano-electronics, optics, materials applications, etc.).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] They exhibit extraordinary strength, unique electrical properties, and are efficient conductors of heat.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Non-carbon nanotubes have also been synthesized.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Carbon nanotubes are a members of the fullerene structural family, which also includes buckyballs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Whereas buckyballs are spherical in shape, a nanotube is cylindrical, with at least one end typically capped with a hemisphere of the buckyball structure.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Their name is derived from their size, since the diameter of a nanotube is on the order of a few nanometers (approximately 50,000 times smaller than the width of a human hair), while they can be up to several centimeters in length.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] There are two main types of nanotubes: single-walled nanotubes (SWNTs) and multi-walled nanotubes (MWNTs).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] A nanolattice is a synthetic porous material consisting of nanometer-size members patterned into an ordered lattice structure, like a space frame.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The nanolattice is a material class that emerged after 2015.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Nanolattices redefine the limits of the material property space.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Despite consisting of 50-99% air, nanolattices are mechanically robust because they take advantage of size-dependent properties generally seen in nanoparticles, nanowires, and thin films.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The most typical mechanical properties of nanolattices include strength, damage tolerance, and stiffness.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Thus, nanolattices have a wide range of potential applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Schwarzites are negatively curved carbon surfaces originally proposed by decorating triply periodic minimal surfaces with carbon atoms.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The geometric topology of the structure is determined by the presence of ring defects, such as heptagons and octagons, to graphene's hexagonal lattice.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Recent work has proposed zeolite-templated carbons (ZTCs) may be schwarzites.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The name, ZTC, derives from their origin inside the pores of zeolites, crystalline silicon dioxide minerals.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] A vapor of carbon-containing molecules is injected into the zeolite, where the carbon gathers on the pores' walls, creating the negative curve.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Dissolving the zeolite leaves the carbon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] A team generated structures by decorating the pores of a zeolite with carbon through a Monte Carlo method.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Some of the resulting models resemble schwarzite-like structures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It was first produced by Bernard Redfern in the mid-1950s at the laboratories of The Carborundum Company, Manchester, UK.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] He had set out to develop a polymer matrix to mirror a diamond structure and discovered a resole (phenolic) resin that would, with special preparation, set without a catalyst.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Using this resin, the first glassy carbon was produced.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The preparation of glassy carbon involves subjecting the organic precursors to a series of heat treatments at temperatures up to 3000 °C.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Unlike many non-graphitizing carbons, they are impermeable to gases and are chemically extremely inert, especially those prepared at very high temperatures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] It has been demonstrated that the rates of oxidation of certain glassy carbons in oxygen, carbon dioxide or water vapor are lower than those of any other carbon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] They are also highly resistant to attack by acids.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Thus, while normal graphite is reduced to a powder by a mixture of concentrated sulfuric and nitric acids at room temperature, glassy carbon is unaffected by such treatment, even after several months.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Each cluster is about 6 nanometers wide and consists of about 4000 carbon atoms linked in graphite-like sheets that are given negative curvature by the inclusion of heptagons among the regular hexagonal pattern.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] This is the opposite of what happens in the case of buckminsterfullerenes, in which carbon sheets are given positive curvature by the inclusion of pentagons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The large-scale structure of carbon nanofoam is similar to that of an aerogel, but with 1% of the density of previously produced carbon aerogels – only a few times the density of air at sea level.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Unlike carbon aerogels, carbon nanofoam is a poor electrical conductor.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Carbide-derived carbon (CDC) is a family of carbon materials with different surface geometries and carbon ordering that are produced via selective removal of metals from metal carbide precursors, such as TiC, SiC, Ti3AlC2, Mo2C, etc.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] This synthesis is accomplished using chlorine treatment, hydrothermal synthesis, or high-temperature selective metal desorption under vacuum.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] These structures exhibit high porosity and specific surface areas, with highly tunable pore diameters, making them promising materials for supercapacitor-based energy storage, water filtration and capacitive desalinization, catalyst support, and cytokine removal.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Other metastable carbon phases, some diamondlike, have been produced from reactions of SiC or CH3SiCl3 with CF4.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] A one-dimensional carbon polymer with the structure —(C≡C)n—.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Its structure is relatively like that of amorphous carbon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Many other allotropes have been hypothesized but have yet to be synthesized.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The system of carbon allotropes spans an astounding range of extremes, considering that they are all merely structural formations of the same element.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] Despite the hardness of diamonds, the chemical bonds that hold the carbon atoms in diamonds together are actually weaker than those that hold together graphite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] The difference is that in diamond, the bonds form an inflexible three-dimensional lattice.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/allotropes-of-carbon] In graphite, the atoms are tightly bonded into sheets, but the sheets can slide easily over each other, making graphite soft.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] Buckypaper is a macroscopic aggregate of carbon nanotubes (CNT), or "buckytubes".
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] It owes its name to the buckminsterfullerene, the 60 carbon fullerene (an allotrope of carbon with similar bonding that is sometimes referred to as a "Buckyball" in honor of R.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] The generally accepted methods of making CNT films involves the use of surfactants, such as Triton X-100 and sodium lauryl sulfate, which improves their dispersibility in aqueous solution.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] These suspensions can then be membrane filtered under positive or negative pressure to yield uniform films.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] The van der Waals force's interaction between the nanotube surface and the surfactant can often be mechanically strong and quite stable and therefore there are no assurances that all the surfactant is removed from the CNT film after formation.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] Washing with methanol, an effective solvent in the removal of Triton X, was found to cause cracking and deformation of the film.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] It has also been found that Triton X can lead to cell lysis and in turn tissue inflammatory responses even at low concentrations.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] In order to avoid adverse side-effects from the possible presence of surfactants, an alternative casting process can be used involving a frit compression method that did not require the use of surfactants or surface modification.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] The dimensions can be controlled through the size of the syringe housing and through the mass of carbon nanotubes added.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] The frit compression method allows rapid casting of buckypaper and buckydiscs with recovery of the casting solvent and control over the 2D and 3D geometry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] Aligned multi-walled carbon nanotube (MWNT) growth has been used in CNT film synthesis through the domino effect.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] In this process, "forests" of MWNTs are pushed flat in a single direction, compressing their vertical orientation into the horizontal plane, which results in the formation of high-purity buckypaper with no further purification or treatment required.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] By comparison, when a buckypaper sample was formed from the 1 ton compression of chemical vapor deposition (CVD) generated MWNT powder, any application of a solvent led to the immediate swelling of the film till it reverted into particulate matter.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] It appears that for the CNT powder used, compression alone was insufficient to generate robust buckypaper and highlights that the aligned growth methodology generates *in situ* tube-tube interactions not found in CVD CNT powder and are preserved through to the domino pushing formation of buckypaper.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] Recently, a new scalable CNT film fabrication method has been developed: Surface-Engineered Tape Casting (SETC) technique.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] The SETC technique solves the main challenge of tape-casting which is the detachment of the dried and the typically sticky CNT film from the supporting-substrate.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] To achieve a perfect detached film, the supporting-substrate has to be engineered with micro-pyramid pore structure morphology.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] SETC produces large area films from any commercially available carbon nanotubes with tunable length, thickness, density and composition.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] Buckypaper is one tenth the weight yet potentially 500 times stronger than steel when its sheets are stacked to form a composite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/buckypaper] It could disperse heat like brass or steel and it could conduct electricity like copper or silicon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A **carbon nanotube** (**CNT**) is a tube made of carbon with a diameter in the nanometre range (nanoscale).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] They are one of the allotropes of carbon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanotubes can exhibit remarkable properties, such as exceptional tensile strength and thermal conductivity because of their nanostructure and strength of the bonds between carbon atoms.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Some SWCNT structures exhibit high electrical conductivity while others are semiconductors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In addition, carbon nanotubes can be chemically modified.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These properties are expected to be valuable in many areas of technology, such as electronics, optics, composite materials (replacing or complementing carbon fibres), nanotechnology (including nanomedicine), and other applications of materials science.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These discoveries triggered research that succeeded in greatly increasing the efficiency of the catalytic production technique, and led to an explosion of work to characterise and find applications for SWCNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The true identity of the discoverers of carbon nanotubes is a subject of some controversy.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A 2006 editorial written by Marc Monthioux and Vladimir Kuznetsov in the journal *Carbon* described the origin of the carbon nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A large percentage of academic and popular literature attributes the discovery of hollow, nanometre-size tubes composed of graphitic carbon to Sumio Iijima of NEC in 1991.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] His paper initiated a flurry of excitement and could be credited with inspiring the study of many applications of carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Though Iijima has been given much of the credit for discovering carbon nanotubes, it turns out that the timeline of carbon nanotubes goes back much further than 1991.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Lukyanovich published clear images of 50-nanometre diameter tubes made of carbon in the *Journal of Physical Chemistry Of Russia*.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This discovery was largely unnoticed, as the article was published in Russian, and Western scientists' access to Soviet press was limited during the Cold War.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In 1976, Morinobu Endo of CNRS observed hollow tubes of rolled up graphite sheets synthesised by a chemical vapour-growth technique.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The first specimens observed would later come to be known as single-walled carbon nanotubes (SWNTs).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Endo, in his early review of vapor-phase-grown carbon fibers (VPCF), also reminded us that he had observed a hollow tube, linearly extended with parallel carbon layer faces near the fiber core.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This appears to be the observation of multi-walled carbon nanotubes at the center of the fiber.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Mass-produced MWCNTs are strongly related to the VPGCF developed by Endo.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In fact, they call it the "Endo process", out of respect for his early work and patents.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In 1979, John Abrahamson presented evidence of carbon nanotubes at the 14th Biennial Conference of Carbon at Pennsylvania State University.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The conference paper described carbon nanotubes as carbon fibers that were produced on carbon anodes during arc discharge.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A characterization of these fibers was given, as well as hypotheses for their growth in a nitrogen atmosphere at low pressures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In 1981, a group of Soviet scientists published the results of chemical and structural characterization of carbon nanoparticles produced by a thermocatalytic disproportionation of carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Using TEM images and XRD patterns, the authors suggested that their "carbon multi-layer tubular crystals" were formed by rolling graphene layers into cylinders.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] They speculated that via this rolling, many different arrangements of graphene hexagonal nets are possible.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] They suggested two such possible arrangements: a circular arrangement (armchair nanotube); and a spiral, helical arrangement (chiral tube).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Nanotube research accelerated greatly following the independent discoveries by Iijima and Ichihashi at NEC and Bethune *et al.* at IBM of methods to specifically produce *single-walled* carbon nanotubes by adding transition-metal catalysts to the carbon in an arc discharge.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Thess et al. refined this catalytic method by vaporizing the carbon/transition-metal combination in a high-temperature furnace, which greatly improved the yield and purity of the SWNTs and made them widely available for characterization and application experiments.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The arc discharge technique, well known to produce the famed Buckminsterfullerene, thus played a role in the discoveries of both multi- and single-wall nanotubes, extending the run of serendipitous discoveries relating to fullerenes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The discovery of nanotubes remains a contentious issue.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Many believe that Iijima's report in 1991 is of particular importance because it brought carbon nanotubes into the awareness of the scientific community as a whole.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In 2020, during an archaeological excavation of Keezhadi in Tamil Nadu, India, ~2600-year-old pottery was discovered whose coatings appear to contain carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The robust mechanical properties of the nanotubes are partially why the coatings have lasted for so many years, say the scientists.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The structure of an ideal (infinitely long) single-walled carbon nanotube is that of a regular hexagonal lattice drawn on an infinite cylindrical surface, whose vertices are the positions of the carbon atoms.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Since the length of the carbon-carbon bonds is fairly fixed, there are constraints on the diameter of the cylinder and the arrangement of the atoms on it.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In the study of nanotubes, one defines a zigzag path on a graphene-like lattice as a path that turns 60 degrees, alternating left and right, after stepping through each bond.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] It is also conventional to define an armchair path as one that makes two left turns of 60 degrees followed by two right turns every four steps.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] On some carbon nanotubes, there is a closed zigzag path that goes around the tube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] One says that the tube is of the **zigzag type** or configuration, or simply is a **zigzag nanotube**.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] If the tube is instead encircled by a closed armchair path, it is said to be of the **armchair type**, or an **armchair nanotube**.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] An infinite nanotube that is of one type consists entirely of closed paths of that type, connected to each other.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The zigzag and armchair configurations are not the only structures that a single-walled nanotube can have.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The two halves of the atom *A* will end up on opposite edges of the strip, over two atoms *A1* and *A2* of the graphene.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The line from *A1* to *A2* will correspond to the circumference of the cylinder that went through the atom *A*, and will be perpendicular to the edges of the strip.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In the graphene lattice, the atoms can be split into two classes, depending on the directions of their three bonds.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Half the atoms have their three bonds directed the same way, and half have their three bonds rotated 180 degrees relative to the first half.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The atoms *A1* and *A2*, which correspond to the same atom *A* on the cylinder, must be in the same class.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] It follows that the circumference of the tube and the angle of the strip are not arbitrary, because they are constrained to the lengths and directions of the lines that connect pairs of graphene atoms in the same class.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Let ***u*** and ***v*** be two linearly independent vectors that connect the graphene atom *A1* to two of its nearest atoms with the same bond directions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These are the graphene's lattice vectors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] For example, if one numbers consecutive carbons around a graphene cell with C1 to C6, then ***u*** can be the vector from C1 to C3, and ***v*** the vector from C1 to C5.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Then, for any other atom *A2* with same class as *A1*, the vector from *A1* to *A2* can be written as a linear combination *n* ***u*** + *m* ***v***, where *n* and *m* are integers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] And, conversely, each pair of integers (*n*,*m*) defines a possible position for *A2*.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Given *n* and *m*, one can reverse this theoretical operation by drawing the vector ***w*** on the graphene lattice, cutting a strip of the latter along lines perpendicular to ***w*** through its endpoints *A1* and *A2*, and rolling the strip into a cylinder so as to bring those two points together.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] If this construction is applied to a pair (*k*,0), the result is a zigzag nanotube, with closed zigzag paths of 2*k* atoms.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] If it is applied to a pair (*k*,*k*), one obtains an armchair tube, with closed armchair paths of 4*k* atoms.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The structure of the nanotube is not changed if the strip is rotated by 60 degrees clockwise around *A1* before applying the hypothetical reconstruction above.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Such a rotation changes the corresponding pair (*n*,*m*) to the pair (−2*m*,*n*+*m*).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] It follows that many possible positions of *A2* relative to *A1* — that is, many pairs (*n*,*m*) — correspond to the same arrangement of atoms on the nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In particular, the pairs (*k*,0) and (0,*k*) describe the same nanotube geometry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These redundancies can be avoided by considering only pairs (*n*,*m*) such that *n* > 0 and *m* ≥ 0; that is, where the direction of the vector ***w*** lies between those of ***u*** (inclusive) and ***v*** (exclusive).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] It can be verified that every nanotube has exactly one pair (*n*,*m*) that satisfies those conditions, which is called the tube's **type**.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Conversely, for every type there is a hypothetical nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In fact, two nanotubes have the same type if and only if one can be conceptually rotated and translated so as to match the other exactly.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] If the diagram is drawn with ***u*** horizontal, the latter is the tilt of the strip away from the vertical.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A nanotube is chiral if it has type (*n*,*m*), with *m* > 0 and *m* ≠ *n*; then its enantiomer (mirror image) has type (*m*,*n*), which is different from (*n*,*m*).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This operation corresponds to mirroring the unrolled strip about the line *L* through *A1* that makes an angle of 30 degrees clockwise from the direction of the ***u*** vector (that is, with the direction of the vector ***u***+***v***).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The only types of nanotubes that are achiral are the (*k*,0) "zigzag" tubes and the (*k*,*k*) "armchair" tubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] If two enantiomers are to be considered the same structure, then one may consider only types (*n*,*m*) with 0 ≤ *m* ≤ *n* and *n* > 0.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Then the angle *α* between ***u*** and ***w***, which may range from 0 to 30 degrees (inclusive both), is called the "chiral angle" of the nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These formulas are only approximate, especially for small *n* and *m* where the bonds are strained, and they do not take into account the thickness of the wall.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] where arg(*x*,*y*) is the clockwise angle between the *X*-axis and the vector (*x*,*y*); a function that is available in many programming languages as `atan2`(*y*,*x*).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] If *n* and *m* are too small, the structure described by the pair (*n*,*m*) will describe a molecule that cannot be reasonably called a "tube", and may not even be stable.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] For example, the structure theoretically described by the pair (1,0) (the limiting "zigzag" type) would be just a chain of carbons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] That is a real molecule, the carbyne; which has some characteristics of nanotubes (such as orbital hybridization, high tensile strength, etc.) — but has no hollow space, and may not be obtainable as a condensed phase.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The pair (2,0) would theoretically yield a chain of fused 4-cycles; and (1,1), the limiting "armchair" structure, would yield a chain of bi-connected 4-rings.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The thinnest carbon nanotube proper is the armchair structure with type (2,2), which has a diameter of 0.3 nm.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This nanotube was grown inside a multi-walled carbon nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Assigning of the carbon nanotube type was done by a combination of high-resolution transmission electron microscopy (HRTEM), Raman spectroscopy, and density functional theory (DFT) calculations.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The thinnest *freestanding* single-walled carbon nanotube is about 0.43 nm in diameter.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Researchers suggested that it can be either (5,1) or (4,2) SWCNT, but the exact type of the carbon nanotube remains questionable.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] (3,3), (4,3), and (5,1) carbon nanotubes (all about 0.4 nm in diameter) were unambiguously identified using aberration-corrected high-resolution transmission electron microscopy inside double-walled CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The observation of the *longest* carbon nanotubes grown so far, around 0.5 metre (550 mm) long, was reported in 2013.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These nanotubes were grown on silicon substrates using an improved chemical vapor deposition (CVD) method and represent electrically uniform arrays of single-walled carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The *shortest* carbon nanotube can be considered to be the organic compound cycloparaphenylene, which was synthesized in 2008 by Ramesh Jasti.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Other small molecule carbon nanotubes have been synthesized since.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The *highest density* of CNTs was achieved in 2013, grown on a conductive titanium-coated copper surface that was coated with co-catalysts cobalt and molybdenum at lower than typical temperatures of 450 °C.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The tubes averaged a height of 380 nm and a mass density of 1.6 g cm−3.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The material showed ohmic conductivity (lowest resistance ~22 kΩ).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The International Standards Organization typically uses "single-walled carbon nanotube (SWCNT)" or "multi-walled carbon nanotube (MWCNT)" in its documents.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Multi-walled nanotubes (MWNTs) consist of multiple rolled layers (concentric tubes) of graphene.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] There are two models that can be used to describe the structures of multi-walled nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In the *Russian Doll* model, sheets of graphite are arranged in concentric cylinders, e.g., a (0,8) single-walled nanotube (SWNT) within a larger (0,17) single-walled nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In the *Parchment* model, a single sheet of graphite is rolled in around itself, resembling a scroll of parchment or a rolled newspaper.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The interlayer distance in multi-walled nanotubes is close to the distance between graphene layers in graphite, approximately 3.4 Å.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The Russian Doll structure is observed more commonly.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Its individual shells can be described as SWNTs, which can be metallic or semiconducting.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Because of statistical probability and restrictions on the relative diameters of the individual tubes, one of the shells, and thus the whole MWNT, is usually a zero-gap metal.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Double-walled carbon nanotubes (DWNTs) form a special class of nanotubes because their morphology and properties are similar to those of SWNTs but they are more resistant to attacks by chemicals.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This is especially important when it is necessary to graft chemical functions to the surface of the nanotubes (functionalization) to add properties to the CNT.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Covalent functionalization of SWNTs will break some C=C double bonds, leaving "holes" in the structure on the nanotube and thus modifying both its mechanical and electrical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In the case of DWNTs, only the outer wall is modified.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] DWNT synthesis on the gram-scale by the CCVD technique was first proposed in 2003 from the selective reduction of oxide solutions in methane and hydrogen.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The telescopic motion ability of inner shells, allowing them to act as low-friction, low-wear nanobearings and nanosprings, may make them a desirable material in nanoelectromechanical systems (NEMS) .
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The retraction force that occurs to telescopic motion is caused by the Lennard-Jones interaction between shells, and its value is about 1.5 nN.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Junctions between two or more nanotubes have been widely discussed theoretically.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Such junctions are quite frequently observed in samples prepared by arc discharge as well as by chemical vapor deposition.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The electronic properties of such junctions were first considered theoretically by Lambin et al., who pointed out that a connection between a metallic tube and a semiconducting one would represent a nanoscale heterojunction.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Such a junction could therefore form a component of a nanotube-based electronic circuit.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The adjacent image shows a junction between two multiwalled nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Junctions between nanotubes and graphene have been considered theoretically and studied experimentally.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Nanotube-graphene junctions form the basis of pillared graphene, in which parallel graphene sheets are separated by short nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Pillared graphene represents a class of three-dimensional carbon nanotube architectures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Recently, several studies have highlighted the prospect of using carbon nanotubes as building blocks to fabricate three-dimensional macroscopic (>100 nm in all three dimensions) all-carbon devices.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Lalwani et al. have reported a novel radical-initiated thermal crosslinking method to fabricate macroscopic, free-standing, porous, all-carbon scaffolds using single- and multi-walled carbon nanotubes as building blocks.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These scaffolds possess macro-, micro-, and nano-structured pores, and the porosity can be tailored for specific applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These 3D all-carbon scaffolds/architectures may be used for the fabrication of the next generation of energy storage, supercapacitors, field emission transistors, high-performance catalysis, photovoltaics, and biomedical devices, implants, and sensors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanobuds are a newly created material combining two previously discovered allotropes of carbon: carbon nanotubes and fullerenes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In this new material, fullerene-like "buds" are covalently bonded to the outer sidewalls of the underlying carbon nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This hybrid material has useful properties of both fullerenes and carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In particular, they have been found to be exceptionally good field emitters.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In composite materials, the attached fullerene molecules may function as molecular anchors preventing slipping of the nanotubes, thus improving the composite's mechanical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A carbon peapod is a novel hybrid carbon material which traps fullerene inside a carbon nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] It can possess interesting magnetic properties with heating and irradiation.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] It can also be applied as an oscillator during theoretical investigations and predictions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In theory, a nanotorus is a carbon nanotube bent into a torus (doughnut shape).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Nanotori are predicted to have many unique properties, such as magnetic moments 1000 times larger than that previously expected for certain specific radii.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Properties such as magnetic moment, thermal stability, etc. vary widely depending on the radius of the torus and the radius of the tube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Graphenated carbon nanotubes are a relatively new hybrid that combines graphitic foliates grown along the sidewalls of multiwalled or bamboo-style CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The foliate density can vary as a function of deposition conditions (e.g., temperature and time) with their structure ranging from a few layers of graphene (< 10) to thicker, more graphite-like.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The fundamental advantage of an integrated graphene-CNT structure is the high surface area three-dimensional framework of the CNTs coupled with the high edge density of graphene.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Depositing a high density of graphene foliates along the length of aligned CNTs can significantly increase the total charge capacity per unit of nominal area as compared to other carbon nanostructures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Cup-stacked carbon nanotubes (CSCNTs) differ from other quasi-1D carbon structures, which normally behave as quasi-metallic conductors of electrons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] CSCNTs exhibit semiconducting behavior because of the stacking microstructure of graphene layers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Many properties of single-walled carbon nanotubes depend significantly on the (*n*,*m*) type, and this dependence is non-monotonic (see Kataura plot).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In particular, the band gap can vary from zero to about 2 eV and the electrical conductivity can show metallic or semiconducting behavior.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanotubes are the strongest and stiffest materials yet discovered in terms of tensile strength and elastic modulus.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This strength results from the covalent sp2 bonds formed between the individual carbon atoms.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In 2000, a multiwalled carbon nanotube was tested to have a tensile strength of 63 GPa (9,100,000 psi).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] (For illustration, this translates into the ability to endure tension of a weight equivalent to 6,422 kilograms-force (62,980 N; 14,160 lbf) on a cable with cross-section of 1 mm2 (0.0016 sq in)).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Further studies, such as one conducted in 2008, revealed that individual CNT shells have strengths of up to ≈100 GPa (15,000,000 psi), which is in agreement with quantum/atomistic models.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Because carbon nanotubes have a low density for a solid of 1.3 to 1.4 g/cm3, its specific strength of up to 48,000 kN·m/kg is the best of known materials, compared to high-carbon steel's 154 kN·m/kg.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Although the strength of individual CNT shells is extremely high, weak shear interactions between adjacent shells and tubes lead to significant reduction in the effective strength of multiwalled carbon nanotubes and carbon nanotube bundles down to only a few GPa.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This limitation has been recently addressed by applying high-energy electron irradiation, which crosslinks inner shells and tubes, and effectively increases the strength of these materials to ≈60 GPa for multiwalled carbon nanotubes and ≈17 GPa for double-walled carbon nanotube bundles.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] CNTs are not nearly as strong under compression.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Because of their hollow structure and high aspect ratio, they tend to undergo buckling when placed under compressive, torsional, or bending stress.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] On the other hand, there is evidence that in the radial direction they are rather soft.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The first transmission electron microscope observation of radial elasticity suggested that even van der Waals forces can deform two adjacent nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Later, nanoindentations with an atomic force microscope were performed by several groups to quantitatively measure the radial elasticity of multiwalled carbon nanotubes and tapping/contact mode atomic force microscopy was also performed on single-walled carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Their high Young's modulus in the linear direction, of on the order of several GPa (and even up to an experimentally-measured 1.8 TPa, for nanotubes near 2.4 μm in length), further suggests they may be soft in the radial direction.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Unlike graphene, which is a two-dimensional semimetal, carbon nanotubes are either metallic or semiconducting along the tubular axis.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] For a given (*n*,*m*) nanotube, if *n* = *m*, the nanotube is metallic; if *n* − *m* is a multiple of 3 and n ≠ m, then the nanotube is quasi-metallic with a very small band gap, otherwise the nanotube is a moderate semiconductor.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Thus, all armchair (*n* = *m*) nanotubes are metallic, and nanotubes (6,4), (9,1), etc. are semiconducting.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The rule regarding metallic versus semiconductor behavior has exceptions because curvature effects in small-diameter tubes can strongly influence electrical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Thus, a (5,0) SWCNT that should be semiconducting in fact is metallic according to the calculations.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Likewise, zigzag and chiral SWCNTs with small diameters that should be metallic have a finite gap (armchair nanotubes remain metallic).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In theory, metallic nanotubes can carry an electric current density of 4 billion A/cm2, which is more than 1,000 times greater than those of metals such as copper, where for copper interconnects, current densities are limited by electromigration.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanotubes are thus being explored as interconnects and conductivity-enhancing components in composite materials, and many groups are attempting to commercialize highly conducting electrical wire assembled from individual carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Because of its nanoscale cross-section, electrons propagate only along the tube's axis.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] As a result, carbon nanotubes are frequently referred to as one-dimensional conductors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The maximum electrical conductance of a single-walled carbon nanotube is 2*G*0, where *G*0 = 2*e*2/*h* is the conductance of a single ballistic quantum channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Because of the role of the π-electron system in determining the electronic properties of graphene, doping in carbon nanotubes differs from that of bulk crystalline semiconductors from the same group of the periodic table (e.g., silicon).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Graphitic substitution of carbon atoms in the nanotube wall by boron or nitrogen dopants leads to p-type and n-type behavior, respectively, as would be expected in silicon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] However, some non-substitutional (intercalated or adsorbed) dopants introduced into a carbon nanotube, such as alkali metals and electron-rich metallocenes, result in n-type conduction because they donate electrons to the π-electron system of the nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] By contrast, π-electron acceptors such as FeCl3 or electron-deficient metallocenes function as p-type dopants because they draw π-electrons away from the top of the valence band.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Intrinsic superconductivity has been reported, although other experiments found no evidence of this, leaving the claim a subject of debate.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Dubbs Professor of Chemical Engineering at MIT, published department findings on the use of carbon nanotubes to create an electric current.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] By immersing the structures in an organic solvent, the liquid drew electrons out of the carbon particles.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Strano was quoted as saying, "This allows you to do electrochemistry, but with no wires," and represents a significant breakthrough in the technology.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Future applications include powering micro- or nanoscale robots, as well as driving alcohol oxidation reactions, which are important in the chemicals industry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Crystallographic defects also affect the tube's electrical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A common result is lowered conductivity through the defective region of the tube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A defect in metallic armchair-type tubes (which can conduct electricity) can cause the surrounding region to become semiconducting, and single monatomic vacancies induce magnetic properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Semiconducting carbon nanotubes have shown piezoresistive property when applying mechanical force.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The structural deformation causes a change in the band gap which effects the conductance.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This property has the potential to be used in strain sensors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanotubes have useful absorption, photoluminescence (fluorescence), and Raman spectroscopy properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Spectroscopic methods offer the possibility of quick and non-destructive characterization of relatively large amounts of carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These features then determine nearly all other significant optical, mechanical, and electrical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanotube optical properties have been explored for use in applications such as for light-emitting diodes (LEDs) and photo-detectors based on a single nanotube have been produced in the lab.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Their unique feature is not the efficiency, which is yet relatively low, but the narrow selectivity in the wavelength of emission and detection of light and the possibility of its fine-tuning through the nanotube structure.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In addition, bolometer and optoelectronic memory devices have been realised on ensembles of single-walled carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Nanotube fluorescence has been investigated for the purposes of imaging and sensing in biomedical applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] All nanotubes are expected to be very good thermal conductors along the tube, exhibiting a property known as "ballistic conduction", but good insulators lateral to the tube axis.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Measurements show that an individual SWNT has a room-temperature thermal conductivity along its axis of about 3500 W·m−1·K−1; compare this to copper, a metal well known for its good thermal conductivity, which transmits 385 W·m−1·K−1.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] An individual SWNT has a room-temperature thermal conductivity lateral to its axis (in the radial direction) of about 1.52 W·m−1·K−1, which is about as thermally conductive as soil.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Macroscopic assemblies of nanotubes such as films or fibres have reached up to 1500 W·m−1·K−1 so far.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Networks composed of nanotubes demonstrate different values of thermal conductivity, from the level of thermal insulation with the thermal conductivity of 0.1 W·m−1·K−1 to such high values.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] That is dependent on the amount of contribution to the thermal resistance of the system caused by the presence of impurities, misalignments and other factors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The temperature stability of carbon nanotubes is estimated to be up to 2800 °C in vacuum and about 750 °C in air.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Crystallographic defects strongly affect the tube's thermal properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Such defects lead to phonon scattering, which in turn increases the relaxation rate of the phonons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This reduces the mean free path and reduces the thermal conductivity of nanotube structures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Phonon transport simulations indicate that substitutional defects such as nitrogen or boron will primarily lead to the scattering of high-frequency optical phonons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] However, larger-scale defects such as Stone–Wales defects cause phonon scattering over a wide range of frequencies, leading to a greater reduction in thermal conductivity.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Recently, carbon-nanotubes have been shown to have antibacterial properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] They disrupt normal bacterial function by causing physical/mechanical damage, facilitating oxidative stress or lipid extraction, inhibiting bacterial metabolism, and isolating functional sites via wrapping with CNM-containing nanomaterials.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Techniques have been developed to produce nanotubes in sizeable quantities, including arc discharge, laser ablation, chemical vapor deposition (CVD) and high-pressure carbon monoxide disproportionation (HiPCO).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Among these arc discharge, laser ablation are batch by batch process, Chemical Vapor Deposition can be used both for batch by batch or continuous processes, and HiPCO is gas phase continuous process.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Most of these processes take place in a vacuum or with process gases.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The CVD growth method is popular, as it yields high quantity and has a degree of control over diameter, length and morphology.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Using particulate catalysts, large quantities of nanotubes can be synthesized by these methods, and industrialisation is well on its way, with several CNT and CNT fibers factory around the world.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] One problem of CVD processes is the high variability in the nanotube's characteristics.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The HiPCO process advances in catalysis and continuous growth are making CNTs more commercially viable.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The HiPCO process helps in producing high purity single-walled carbon nanotubes in higher quantity.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The HiPCO reactor operates at high temperature 900–1100 °C and high pressure ~30–50 bar.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] It uses carbon monoxide as the carbon source and iron pentacarbonyl or nickel tetracarbonyl as a catalyst.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These catalysts provide a nucleation site for the nanotubes to grow, while cheaper iron-based catalysts like Ferrocene can be used for CVD process.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Vertically aligned carbon nanotube arrays are also grown by thermal chemical vapor deposition.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A substrate (quartz, silicon, stainless steel, carbon fibers, etc.) is coated with a catalytic metal (Fe, Co, Ni) layer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Typically that layer is iron and is deposited via sputtering to a thickness of 1–5 nm.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] A 10–50 nm underlayer of alumina is often also put down on the substrate first.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This imparts controllable wetting and good interfacial properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] When the substrate is heated to the growth temperature (~600 to 850 °C), the continuous iron film breaks up into small islands with each island then nucleating a carbon nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The sputtered thickness controls the island size and this in turn determines the nanotube diameter.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Thinner iron layers drive down the diameter of the islands and drive down the diameter of the nanotubes grown.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The amount of time the metal island can sit at the growth temperature is limited as they are mobile and can merge into larger (but fewer) islands.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Annealing at the growth temperature reduces the site density (number of CNT/mm2) while increasing the catalyst diameter.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The as-prepared carbon nanotubes always have impurities such as other forms of carbon (amorphous carbon, fullerene, etc.) and non-carbonaceous impurities (metal used for catalyst).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These impurities need to be removed to make use of the carbon nanotubes in applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Synthesized carbon nanotubes typically contain impurities and most importantly different chiralities of carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Therefore, multiple methods have been developed to purify them including polymer-assisted, density gradient ultracentrifugation (DGU), chromatography and aqueous two-phase extraction (ATPE).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] These methods have been reviewed in multiple articles.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Certain polymers selectively disperse or wrap CNTs of a particular chirality, metallic character or diameter.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] For example, poly(phenylenevinylenes) disperse CNTs of specific diameters (0.75–0.84 nm) and polyfluorenes are highly selective for semiconducting CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Separation involves mainly two steps: sonicate the mixture (CNTs and polymers in solvent), then centrifuge.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The supernatant will contain the desired CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Density gradient ultracentrifugation is based on the density difference of CNTs, so that different components are layered in centrifuge tubes under centrifugal force.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Chromatography-based methods include size exclusion (SEC), ion-exchange (IEX) and gel chromatography.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] For SEC, CNTs are separated due to the difference in size using a stationary phase with different pore size.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] As for IEX, the separation is achieved based on their differential adsorption and desorption onto chemically functionalized resins packed in an IEX column, so understanding the interaction between CNTs mixtures and resins is important.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The first IEX was reported to separate DNA-SWCNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Gel chromatography is based on the partition of CNTs between stationary and mobile phase.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Semiconducting CNTs are more strongly attracted by gel than metallic CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] While it shows potential, this application is limited to the separation of semiconducting (n,m) species.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] ATPE uses two water-soluble polymers such as polyethylene glycol (PEG) and dextran.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] When mixed, two immiscible aqueous phases form spontaneously, and each of the two phases shows a different affinity to CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Partition depends on the solvation energy difference between two similar phases of microscale volumes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] By changing the separation system or temperatures, and adding strong oxidants, reductants, or salts, the partition of CNTs species into the two phases can be adjusted.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Despite the progress that has been made to separate and purify CNTs, many challenges remain, such as the growth of chirality-controlled CNTs, so that no further purification is needed, or large-scale purification.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Monochiral CNTs have the advantage that they contain fewer or no impurities, and well-defined non-congested optical spectra.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This allows creation of CNT-based biosensors with higher sensitivity and selectivity.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] For example, monochiral SWCNTs are necessary for multiplexed and ratiometric sensing schemes with enhanced sensitivity and biocompatibility.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanotubes can be functionalized to attain desired properties for use in a wide variety of applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The two main methods of carbon nanotube functionalization are covalent and non-covalent modification.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Because of their apparent hydrophobic nature, carbon nanotubes tend to agglomerate, hindering their dispersion in solvents or viscous polymer melts.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The resulting nanotube bundles or aggregates reduce the mechanical performance of the final composite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The surface of the carbon nanotubes can be modified to reduce the hydrophobicity and improve interfacial adhesion to a bulk polymer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Free radical grafting is a promising technique among covalent functionalization methods, in which alkyl or aryl peroxides, substituted anilines, and diazonium salts are used as the starting agents.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Functionalization can improve CNTs characteristically weak dispersibility in many solvents, such as water - a consequence of their strong intermolecular p–p interactions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This can enhance the processing and manipulation of insoluble CNTs, rendering them useful for synthesizing innovative CNT nanofluids with properties that are tunable for a wide range of applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Free radical grafting of macromolecules (as the functional group) onto the surface of CNTs can improve the solubility of CNTs compared to acid treatments which involve the attachment of small molecules such as hydroxyl onto the surface of CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The solubility of CNTs can be improved significantly by free-radical grafting because the large functional molecules facilitate the dispersion of CNTs in a variety of solvents even at a low degree of functionalization.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Recently an environmentally friendly approach has been developed for the covalent functionalization of multi-walled carbon nanotubes (MWCNTs) using clove buds.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] This approach is innovative and green because it does not use toxic and hazardous acids which are typically used in common carbon nanomaterial functionalization procedures.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The MWCNTs are functionalized in one pot using a free radical grafting reaction.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The clove-functionalized MWCNTs are then dispersed in water producing a highly stable multi-walled carbon nanotube aqueous suspension (nanofluids).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The surface of carbon nanotubes can be chemically modified by coating spinel nanoparticles by hydrothermal synthesis and can be used for water oxidation purposes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] In addition, the surface of carbon nanotubes can be fluorinated or halofluorinated by heating while in contact with a fluoroorganic substance, thereby forming partially fluorinated carbons (so-called Fluocar materials) with grafted (halo)fluoroalkyl functionality.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Carbon nanotubes are modelled in a similar manner as traditional composites in which a reinforcement phase is surrounded by a matrix phase.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Idealized models such as cylindrical, hexagonal and square models are common.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The size of the micromechanics model is a function of the studied mechanical properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The concept of representative volume element (RVE) is used to determine the appropriate size and configuration of the computer model to replicate the actual behavior of the CNT-reinforced nanocomposite.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] Depending on the material property of interest (thermal, electrical, modulus, creep), one RVE might predict the property better than the alternatives.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] While the implementation of the ideal model is computationally efficient, they do not represent microstructural features observed in scanning electron microscopy of actual nanocomposites.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] To incorporate realistic modeling, computer models are also generated to incorporate variability such as waviness, orientation and agglomeration of multiwall or single-wall carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] There are many metrology standards and reference materials available for carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] The Canadian National Research Council also offers a certified reference material SWCNT-1 for elemental analysis using neutron activation analysis and inductively coupled plasma mass spectroscopy.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] NIST RM 8281 is a mixture of three lengths of single-wall carbon nanotube.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] For multiwall carbon nanotubes, ISO/TR 10929 identifies the basic properties and the content of impurities, while ISO/TS 11888 describes morphology using scanning electron microscopy, transmission electron microscopy, viscometry, and light scattering analysis.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p01] ISO/TS 10798 is also valid for multiwall carbon nanotubes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) is the leading United States federal agency conducting research and providing guidance on the occupational safety and health implications and applications of nanomaterials.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Early scientific studies have indicated that nanoscale particles may pose a greater health risk than bulk materials due to a relative increase in surface area per unit mass.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Increase in length and diameter of CNT is correlated to increased toxicity and pathological alterations in the lungs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The biological interactions of nanotubes are not well understood, and the field is open to continued toxicological studies.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] It is often difficult to separate confounding factors, and since carbon is relatively biologically inert, some of the toxicity attributed to carbon nanotubes may be instead due to residual metal catalyst contamination.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In previous studies, only Mitsui-7 was reliably demonstrated to be carcinogenic, although for unclear/unknown reasons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Unlike many common mineral fibers (such as asbestos), most SWCNTs and MWCNTs do not fit the size and aspect-ratio criteria to be classified as respirable fibers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In 2013, given that the long-term health effects have not yet been measured, NIOSH published a Current Intelligence Bulletin detailing the potential hazards and recommended exposure limit for carbon nanotubes and fibers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health has determined non-regulatory recommended exposure limits (RELs) of 1 μg/m3 for carbon nanotubes and carbon nanofibers as background-corrected elemental carbon as an 8-hour time-weighted average (TWA) respirable mass concentration.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Although CNT caused pulmonary inflammation and toxicity in mice, exposure to aerosols generated from sanding of composites containing polymer-coated MWCNTs, representative of the actual end-product, did not exert such toxicity.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] As of October 2016, single-wall carbon nanotubes have been registered through the European Union's Registration, Evaluation, Authorization and Restriction of Chemicals (REACH) regulations, based on evaluation of the potentially hazardous properties of SWCNT.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Based on this registration, SWCNT commercialization is allowed in the EU up to 100 metric tons.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The type of SWCNT registered through REACH is limited to the specific type of single-wall carbon nanotubes manufactured by OCSiAl, which submitted the application.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Multi-walled carbon nanotubes (MWCNTs) with lengths ranging from approximately 0.5 to 10 μm have been implicated in severe pulmonary conditions, including asbestosis-like fibrosis and mesothelioma.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Similarly, single-walled carbon nanotubes (SWCNTs) exceeding 10 μm in length can induce granulomatous lesions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In contrast, shorter SWCNTs—particularly those under 300 nm and well-dispersed—are more readily cleared from the body via renal and biliary excretion pathways.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] These shorter, purified SWCNTs have demonstrated significantly reduced inflammatory and cytotoxic responses and, to date, lack conclusive evidence of carcinogenicity.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Agglomerated CNTs tend to form larger, more rigid, and compact structures—morphologically similar to asbestos fibers—compared to the more loosely associated CNT bundles.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Specifically, agglomerated SWCNTs have been shown to induce pronounced granulomatous inflammation, characterized by granuloma formation surrounded by hypertrophic macrophages in seven days post-exposure.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In contrast, well-dispersed SWCNTs elicit significantly milder inflammatory responses.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Beyond metal impurities, the presence of non-metallic contaminants, including amorphous carbon and other carbonaceous byproducts (e.g., polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons can significantly modulate the biological response to CNTs, contributing to cytotoxicity and inflammatory signaling.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Carbon nanotubes are used in multiple industrial and consumer applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] These include battery components, polymer composites, to improve the mechanical, thermal and electrical properties of the bulk product, and as a highly absorptive black paint.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Many other applications are under development, including field effect transistors for electronics, high-strength fabrics and biosensors for biomedical and agricultural applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Because of their relatively large surface area, CNTs are capable of interacting with a wide variety of therapeutic and diagnostic agents (drugs, genes, vaccines, antibodies, biosensors, etc.).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] This can be utilized to assist in drug delivery directly into cells.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In addition, CNTs have recently been used as reinforcements in implants and scaffolds due to their suitable reaction area, high elastic modulus, and load transfer capability.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] CNTs have been shown to increase the effectiveness of bioactive coatings for the attachment, proliferation, and differentiation of osteoblasts, and has been used as a bone substitution material.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] CNTs may be used as reinforcing materials for chitosan-containing coatings used on implants and medical scaffolds.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] SWCNTs have nanoscale dimensions that match the size of biological species.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Due to this size compatibility and their large surface-to-volume ratio, they are sensitive to changes in their chemical environment.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Through covalent and non-covalent surface functionalization, SWCNTs can be precisely tailored for selective molecular interactions with a target analyte.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The SWCNT represents the transduction unit that converts the interaction into a signal change (optical or electrical).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Due to continuous progress in the development of detection strategies, there are numerous examples of the use of SWCNTs as highly sensitive nanosensors (even down to the single molecule level) for a variety of important biomolecules.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Examples include the detection of reactive oxygen and nitrogen species, neurotransmitters, other small molecules, lipids, proteins, sugars, DNA/RNA, enzymes as well as bacteria.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The signal change manifests itself in an increase or decrease in the current (electrical) or in a change in the intensity or wavelength of the fluorescence emission (optical).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Depending on the type of application, both electrical or optical signal transmission can be advantageous.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] For sensitive measurement of electronic changes, field-effect transistors (FET) are often used in which the flow of charges within the SWCNTs is measured.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The FET structures allow easy on-chip integration and can be parallelized to detect multiple target analytes simultaneously.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] However, such sensors are more invasive for in vivo applications, as the entire device has to be inserted into the body.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Optical detection with semiconducting SWCNTs is based on the radiative recombination of excitons in the near-infrared (NIR) by prior optical (fluorescence) or electrical excitation (electroluminescence).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The emission in the NIR enables detection in the biological transparency window, where optical sensor applications benefit from reduced scattering and autofluorescence of biological samples and consequently a high signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Compared to optical sensors in the UV or visible range, the penetration depth in biological tissue is also increased.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In addition to the advantage of a contactless readout SWCNTs have excellent photostability, which enables long-term sensor applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Furthermore, the nanoscale size of SWCNTs allows dense coating of surfaces which enables chemical imaging, e.g. of cellular release processes with high spatial and temporal resolution.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Detection of several target analytes is possible by the spatial arrangement of different SWCNT sensors in arrays or by hyperspectral detection based on monochiral SWCNT sensors that emit at different emission wavelengths.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] For fluorescence applications, however, optical filters to distinguish between excitation and emission and a NIR-sensitive detector must be used.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Standard silicon detectors can also be used if monochiral SWCNTs (extractable by special purification processes) emitting closer to the visible range (800 – 900 nm) are used.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In order to avoid susceptibility of optical sensors to fluctuating ambient light, internal references such as SWCNTs that are modified to be non-responsive or stable NIR emitters can be used.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] An alternative is to measure fluorescence lifetimes instead of fluorescence intensities.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Overall, SWCNTs therefore have great potential as building blocks for various biosensors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] To render SWCNTs suitable for biosensing, their surface needs to be modified to ensure colloidal stability and provide a handle for biological recognition.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Therefore, biosensing and surface modifications (functionalization) are closely related.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] In industry, SWCNTs are already used as sensors in the detection of gases and odors in the form of an electronic nose or in enzyme screening.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Carbon nanotubes can serve as additives to various structural materials.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] For instance, nanotubes form a tiny portion of the material(s) in some (primarily carbon fiber) baseball bats, golf clubs, car parts, or damascus steel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] IBM expected carbon nanotube transistors to be used on Integrated Circuits by 2020.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The strength and flexibility of carbon nanotubes makes them of potential use in controlling other nanoscale structures, which suggests they will have an important role in nanotechnology engineering.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The highest tensile strength of an individual multi-walled carbon nanotube has been tested to be 63 GPa.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Carbon nanotubes were found in Damascus steel from the 17th century, possibly helping to account for the legendary strength of the swords made of it.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Recently, several studies have highlighted the prospect of using carbon nanotubes as building blocks to fabricate three-dimensional macroscopic (>1mm in all three dimensions) all-carbon devices.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Lalwani et al. have reported a novel radical initiated thermal crosslinking method to fabricated macroscopic, free-standing, porous, all-carbon scaffolds using single- and multi-walled carbon nanotubes as building blocks.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] These scaffolds possess macro-, micro-, and nano- structured pores and the porosity can be tailored for specific applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] These 3D all-carbon scaffolds/architectures may be used for the fabrication of the next generation of energy storage, supercapacitors, field emission transistors, high-performance catalysis, photovoltaics, and biomedical devices and implants.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] CNTs are potential candidates for future via and wire material in nano-scale VLSI circuits.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Eliminating electromigration reliability concerns that plague modern Cu interconnects, isolated (single and multi-wall) CNTs can carry current densities in excess of 1000 MA/cm2 without electromigration damage.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Single-walled nanotubes are likely candidates for miniaturizing electronics.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The most basic building block of these systems is an electric wire, and SWNTs with diameters of an order of a nanometre can be excellent conductors.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] One useful application of SWNTs is in the development of the first intermolecular field-effect transistors (FET).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The first intermolecular logic gate using SWCNT FETs was made in 2001.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] A logic gate requires both a p-FET and an n-FET.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Because SWNTs are p-FETs when exposed to oxygen and n-FETs otherwise, it is possible to expose half of an SWNT to oxygen and protect the other half from it.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The resulting SWNT acts as a *not* logic gate with both p- and n-type FETs in the same molecule.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Large quantities of pure CNTs can be made into a freestanding sheet or film by surface-engineered tape-casting (SETC) fabrication technique which is a scalable method to fabricate flexible and foldable sheets with superior properties.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Another reported form factor is CNT fiber (a.k.a. filament) by wet spinning.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The fiber is either directly spun from the synthesis pot or spun from pre-made dissolved CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Individual fibers can be turned into a yarn.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Apart from its strength and flexibility, the main advantage is making an electrically conducting yarn.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The electronic properties of individual CNT fibers (i.e. bundle of individual CNT) are governed by the two-dimensional structure of CNTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] The fibers were measured to have a resistivity only one order of magnitude higher than metallic conductors at 300 K (27 °C; 80 °F).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] By further optimizing the CNTs and CNT fibers, CNT fibers with improved electrical properties could be developed.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] CNT-based yarns are suitable for applications in energy and electrochemical water treatment when coated with an ion-exchange membrane.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] Also, CNT-based yarns could replace copper as a winding material.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/carbon-nanotube-p02] (2015) have built a motor using CNT winding.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] In geometry, a figure is **chiral** (and said to have **chirality**) if it is not identical to its mirror image, or, more precisely, if it cannot be mapped to its mirror image by rotations and translations alone.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] An object that is not chiral is said to be *achiral*.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] A chiral object and its mirror image are said to be **enantiomorphs**.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] The word *chirality* is derived from the Greek χείρ (cheir), the hand, the most familiar chiral object; the word *enantiomorph* stems from the Greek ἐναντίος (enantios) 'opposite' + μορφή (morphe) 'form'.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] Some chiral three-dimensional objects, such as the helix, can be assigned a right or left handedness, according to the right-hand rule.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] Many other familiar objects exhibit the same chiral symmetry of the human body, such as gloves and shoes.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] Right shoes differ from left shoes only by being mirror images of each other.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] In contrast thin gloves may not be considered chiral if you can wear them inside-out.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] The J-, L-, S- and Z-shaped *tetrominoes* of the popular video game Tetris also exhibit chirality, but only in a two-dimensional space.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] Individually they contain no mirror symmetry in the plane.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] A figure is achiral if and only if its symmetry group contains at least one *orientation-reversing* isometry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] In Euclidean geometry any isometry can be written as $v\mapsto Av+b$ with an orthogonal matrix A and a vector b .
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] The determinant of A is either 1 or −1 then.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] If it is −1 the isometry is orientation-reversing, otherwise it is orientation-preserving.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] A general definition of chirality based on group theory exists.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] It does not refer to any orientation concept: an isometry is direct if and only if it is a product of squares of isometries, and if not, it is an indirect isometry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] The resulting chirality definition works in spacetime.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] In two dimensions, every figure which possesses an axis of symmetry is achiral, and it can be shown that every *bounded* achiral figure must have an axis of symmetry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] (An *axis of symmetry* of a figure F is a line L , such that F is invariant under the mapping $(x,y)\mapsto (x,-y)$ , when L is chosen to be the x -axis of the coordinate system.) For that reason, a triangle is achiral if it is equilateral or isosceles, and is chiral if it is scalene.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] But if one prolongs the pattern in both directions to infinity, one receives an (unbounded) achiral figure which has no axis of symmetry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] Its symmetry group is a frieze group generated by a single glide reflection.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] In three dimensions, every figure that possesses a mirror plane of symmetry *S1*, an inversion center of symmetry *S2*, or a higher improper rotation (rotoreflection) *Sn* axis of symmetry is achiral.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] (A *plane of symmetry* of a figure F is a plane P , such that F is invariant under the mapping $(x,y,z)\mapsto (x,y,-z)$ , when P is chosen to be the x - y -plane of the coordinate system.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] A *center of symmetry* of a figure F is a point C , such that F is invariant under the mapping $(x,y,z)\mapsto (-x,-y,-z)$ , when C is chosen to be the origin of the coordinate system.) Note, however, that there are achiral figures lacking both plane and center of symmetry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] which is invariant under the orientation reversing isometry $(x,y,z)\mapsto (-y,x,-z)$ and thus achiral, but it has neither plane nor center of symmetry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] also is achiral as the origin is a center of symmetry, but it lacks a plane of symmetry.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] A knot is called achiral if it can be continuously deformed into its mirror image, otherwise it is called a chiral knot.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/chirality-mathematics] For example, the unknot and the figure-eight knot are achiral, whereas the trefoil knot is chiral.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The **field-effect transistor** (**FET**) is a type of transistor that uses an electric field to control the current through a semiconductor.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] It comes in two types: junction FET (JFET) and metal–oxide–semiconductor FET (MOSFET).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs have three terminals: source, gate, and drain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs control the current by the application of a voltage to the gate, which in turn alters the conductivity between the drain and source.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs are also known as **unipolar transistors** since they involve single-carrier-type operation.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] That is, FETs use either electrons (n-channel) or holes (p-channel) as charge carriers in their operation, but not both.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Field-effect transistors generally display very high input impedance at low frequencies.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The most widely used field-effect transistor is the MOSFET, which became the most common type of transistor in computers, electronics, and communications technology due to its high scalability and low power consumption.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The concept of the FET was first proposed by Julius Edgar Lilienfeld in 1925 and by Oskar Heil in 1934, though neither was able to build a working device.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The first successful FET, the junction field-effect transistor, was practically demonstrated in 1953.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The MOSFET was later invented by Mohamed Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs in 1960 and went on to become the foundation of modern integrated circuit technology.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs can be constructed from a variety of semiconductors, with silicon being by far the most common.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] More unusual materials include amorphous silicon, polycrystalline silicon, and organic semiconductors used in organic field-effect transistors (OFETs).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Many distinct types of FETs exist, including the MOSFET, JFET, MESFET, HEMT, FinFET, and TFET, among others, each suited to different applications ranging from signal amplification to power control and biosensing.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs offer several advantages over bipolar junction transistors (BJTs), including very high input impedance, lower noise in sensitive electronics, excellent thermal stability, and extremely low power draw when switching.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] However, FETs also have disadvantages such as a relatively low gain–bandwidth product, susceptibility to overload voltages, and significant power dissipation during switching transitions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The concept of a field-effect transistor (FET) was first patented by the Austro-Hungarian born physicist Julius Edgar Lilienfeld in 1925 and by Oskar Heil in 1934, but they were unable to build a working practical semiconducting device based on the concept.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The transistor effect was later observed and explained by John Bardeen and Walter Houser Brattain while working under William Shockley at Bell Labs in 1947, shortly after Lilienfeld's 17-year patent term expired.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Shockley initially attempted to build a working FET by trying to modulate the conductivity of a semiconductor, but was unsuccessful, mainly due to problems with the surface states, the dangling bond, and the germanium and copper compound materials.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In the course of trying to understand the mysterious reasons behind their failure to build a working FET, Bardeen and Brattain instead invented the point-contact transistor in 1947, which was followed by Shockley's bipolar junction transistor in 1948.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The first FET device to be successfully built was the junction field-effect transistor (JFET).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] A JFET was first patented by Heinrich Welker in 1945.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The static induction transistor (SIT), a type of JFET with a short channel, was invented by Japanese engineers Jun-ichi Nishizawa and Y.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Following Shockley's theoretical treatment on the JFET in 1952, a working practical JFET was built by George C.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] However, the JFET still had issues affecting junction transistors in general.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Junction transistors were relatively bulky devices that were difficult to manufacture on a mass-production basis, which limited them to a number of specialised applications.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] By the mid-1950s, researchers had largely given up on the FET concept, and instead focused on bipolar junction transistor (BJT) technology.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The foundations of MOSFET technology were laid down by the work of William Shockley, John Bardeen and Walter Brattain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Shockley independently envisioned the FET concept in 1945, but he was unable to build a working device.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The next year Bardeen explained his failure in terms of surface states.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Bardeen applied the theory of surface states on semiconductors (previous work on surface states was done by Shockley in 1939 and Igor Tamm in 1932) and realized that the external field was blocked at the surface because of extra electrons which are drawn to the semiconductor surface.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Electrons become trapped in those localized states forming an inversion layer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Bardeen's hypothesis marked the birth of surface physics.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Bardeen then decided to make use of an inversion layer instead of the very thin layer of semiconductor which Shockley had envisioned in his FET designs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Based on his theory, in 1948 Bardeen patented the progenitor of MOSFET, an insulated-gate FET (IGFET) with an inversion layer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The inversion layer confines the flow of minority carriers, increasing modulation and conductivity, although its electron transport depends on the gate's insulator or quality of oxide if used as an insulator, deposited above the inversion layer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Bardeen's patent as well as the concept of an inversion layer forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In 1976 Shockley described Bardeen's surface state hypothesis "as one of the most significant research ideas in the semiconductor program".
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] After Bardeen's surface state theory the trio tried to overcome the effect of surface states.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In late 1947, Robert Gibney and Brattain suggested the use of electrolyte placed between metal and semiconductor to overcome the effects of surface states.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Their FET device worked, but amplification was poor.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Bardeen went further and suggested to rather focus on the conductivity of the inversion layer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Further experiments led them to replace electrolyte with a solid oxide layer in the hope of getting better results.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Their goal was to penetrate the oxide layer and get to the inversion layer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] However, Bardeen suggested they switch from silicon to germanium and in the process their oxide got inadvertently washed off.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] They stumbled upon a completely different transistor, the point-contact transistor.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Lillian Hoddeson argues that "had Brattain and Bardeen been working with silicon instead of germanium they would have stumbled across a successful field effect transistor".
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] By the end of the first half of the 1950s, following theoretical and experimental work of Bardeen, Brattain, Kingston, Morrison and others, it became more clear that there were two types of surface states.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Fast surface states were found to be associated with the bulk and a semiconductor/oxide interface.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Slow surface states were found to be associated with the oxide layer because of adsorption of atoms, molecules and ions by the oxide from the ambient.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The latter were found to be much more numerous and to have much longer relaxation times.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] At the time Philo Farnsworth and others came up with various methods of producing atomically clean semiconductor surfaces.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In 1955, Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derrick accidentally covered the surface of silicon wafer with a layer of silicon dioxide.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] They showed that oxide layer prevented certain dopants into the silicon wafer, while allowing for others, thus discovering the passivating effect of oxidation on the semiconductor surface.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Their further work demonstrated how to etch small openings in the oxide layer to diffuse dopants into selected areas of the silicon wafer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In 1957, they published a research paper and patented their technique summarizing their work.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The technique they developed is known as oxide diffusion masking, which would later be used in the fabrication of MOSFET devices.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] At Bell Labs, the importance of Frosch's technique was immediately realized.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Results of their work circulated around Bell Labs in the form of BTL memos before being published in 1957.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] At Shockley Semiconductor, Shockley had circulated the preprint of their article in December 1956 to all his senior staff, including Jean Hoerni.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In 1955, Ian Munro Ross filed a patent for a FeFET or MFSFET.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Its structure was like that of a modern inversion channel MOSFET, but ferroelectric material was used as a dielectric/insulator instead of oxide.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] He envisioned it as a form of memory, years before the floating gate MOSFET.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In February 1957, John Wallmark filed a patent for FET in which germanium monoxide was used as a gate dielectric, but he didn't pursue the idea.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In his other patent filed the same year he described a double gate FET.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In March 1957, in his laboratory notebook, Ernesto Labate, a research scientist at Bell Labs, conceived of a device similar to the later proposed MOSFET, although Labate's device didn't explicitly use silicon dioxide as an insulator.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In 1955, Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derrick accidentally grew a layer of silicon dioxide over the silicon wafer, for which they observed surface passivation effects.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] By 1957 Frosch and Derrick, using masking and predeposition, were able to manufacture silicon dioxide transistors and showed that silicon dioxide insulated, protected silicon wafers and prevented dopants from diffusing into the wafer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Spitzer studied the mechanism of thermally grown oxides and fabricated a high quality Si/SiO2 stack in 1960.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Following this research, Mohamed Atalla and Dawon Kahng proposed a silicon MOS transistor in 1959 and successfully demonstrated a working MOS device with their Bell Labs team in 1960.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] With its high scalability, and much lower power consumption and higher density than bipolar junction transistors, the MOSFET made it possible to build high-density integrated circuits.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The MOSFET is also capable of handling higher power than the JFET.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The MOSFET was the first truly compact transistor that could be miniaturised and mass-produced for a wide range of uses.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The MOSFET thus became the most common type of transistor in computers, electronics, and communications technology (such as smartphones).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The US Patent and Trademark Office calls it a "groundbreaking invention that transformed life and culture around the world".
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In 1948, Bardeen and Brattain patented the progenitor of MOSFET, an insulated-gate FET (IGFET) with an inversion layer.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Their patent and the concept of an inversion layer, forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] CMOS (complementary MOS), a semiconductor device fabrication process for MOSFETs, was developed by Chih-Tang Sah and Frank Wanlass at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The first report of a floating-gate MOSFET was made by Dawon Kahng and Simon Sze in 1967.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The concept of a double-gate thin-film transistor (TFT) was proposed by H.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] A double-gate MOSFET was first demonstrated in 1984 by Electrotechnical Laboratory researchers Toshihiro Sekigawa and Yutaka Hayashi.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FinFET (fin field-effect transistor), a type of 3D non-planar multi-gate MOSFET, originated from the research of Digh Hisamoto and his team at Hitachi Central Research Laboratory in 1989.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs can be majority-charge-carrier devices, in which the current is carried predominantly by majority carriers, or minority-charge-carrier devices, in which the current is mainly due to a flow of minority carriers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The device consists of an active **channel** through which charge carriers, electrons or holes, flow from the source to the drain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Source and drain terminal conductors are connected to the semiconductor through ohmic contacts.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The conductivity of the channel is a function of the potential applied across the gate and source terminals.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Drain (D), through which the carriers leave the channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Conventionally, current leaving the channel at D is designated by ID.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Gate (G), the terminal that modulates the channel conductivity.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] By applying voltage to G, one can control ID.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] All FETs have *source*, *drain*, and *gate* terminals that correspond roughly to the *emitter*, *collector*, and *base* of BJTs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The size of the gate, length *L* in the diagram, is the distance between source and drain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The *width* is the extension of the transistor, in the direction perpendicular to the cross section in the diagram (i.e., into/out of the screen).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Typically the width is much larger than the length of the gate.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] A gate length of 1 μm limits the upper frequency to about 5 GHz, 0.2 μm to about 30 GHz.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The names of the terminals refer to their functions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The gate terminal may be thought of as controlling the opening and closing of a physical gate.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] This gate permits electrons to flow through or blocks their passage by creating or eliminating a channel between the source and drain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Electron-flow from the source terminal towards the drain terminal is influenced by an applied voltage.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The body simply refers to the bulk of the semiconductor in which the gate, source and drain lie.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Usually the body terminal is connected to the highest or lowest voltage within the circuit, depending on the type of the FET.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The body terminal and the source terminal are sometimes connected together since the source is often connected to the highest or lowest voltage within the circuit, although there are several uses of FETs which do not have such a configuration, such as transmission gates and cascode circuits.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Unlike BJTs, the vast majority of FETs are electrically symmetrical.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The source and drain terminals can thus be interchanged in practical circuits with no change in operating characteristics or function.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] This can be confusing when FET's appear to be connected "backwards" in schematic diagrams and circuits because the physical orientation of the FET was decided for other reasons, such as printed circuit layout considerations.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The FET controls the flow of electrons (or electron holes) from the source to drain by affecting the size and shape of a "conductive channel" created and influenced by voltage (or lack of voltage) applied across the gate and source terminals.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] (For simplicity, this discussion assumes that the body and source are connected.) This conductive channel is the "stream" through which electrons flow from source to drain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In an **n-channel** "depletion-mode" device, a negative gate-to-source voltage causes a depletion region to expand in width and encroach on the channel from the sides, narrowing the channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] If the active region expands to completely close the channel, the resistance of the channel from source to drain becomes large, and the FET is effectively turned off like a switch (see right figure, when there is very small current).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] This is called "pinch-off", and the voltage at which it occurs is called the "pinch-off voltage".
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Conversely, a positive gate-to-source voltage increases the channel size and allows electrons to flow easily (see right figure, when there is a conduction channel and current is large).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In an n-channel "enhancement-mode" device, a conductive channel does not exist naturally within the transistor, and a positive gate-to-source voltage is necessary to create one.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The positive voltage attracts free-floating electrons within the body towards the gate, forming a conductive channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] But first, enough electrons must be attracted near the gate to counter the dopant ions added to the body of the FET; this forms a region with no mobile carriers called a depletion region, and the voltage at which this occurs is referred to as the threshold voltage of the FET.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Further gate-to-source voltage increase will attract even more electrons towards the gate which are able to create an active channel from source to drain; this process is called *inversion*.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In a **p-channel** "depletion-mode" device, a positive voltage from gate to body widens the depletion layer by forcing electrons to the gate-insulator/semiconductor interface, leaving exposed a carrier-free region of immobile, positively charged acceptor ions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Conversely, in a p-channel "enhancement-mode" device, a conductive region does not exist and negative voltage must be used to generate a conduction channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] For either enhancement- or depletion-mode devices, at drain-to-source voltages much less than gate-to-source voltages, changing the gate voltage will alter the channel resistance, and drain current will be proportional to drain voltage (referenced to source voltage).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In this mode the FET operates like a variable resistor and the FET is said to be operating in a linear mode or ohmic mode.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] If drain-to-source voltage is increased, this creates a significant asymmetrical change in the shape of the channel due to a gradient of voltage potential from source to drain.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The shape of the inversion region becomes "pinched-off" near the drain end of the channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] If drain-to-source voltage is increased further, the pinch-off point of the channel begins to move away from the drain towards the source.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The FET is said to be in *saturation mode*; although some authors refer to it as *active mode*, for a better analogy with bipolar transistor operating regions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The saturation mode, or the region between ohmic and saturation, is used when amplification is needed.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The in-between region is sometimes considered to be part of the ohmic or linear region, even where drain current is not approximately linear with drain voltage.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Even though the conductive channel formed by gate-to-source voltage no longer connects source to drain during saturation mode, carriers are not blocked from flowing.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Considering again an n-channel enhancement-mode device, a depletion region exists in the p-type body, surrounding the conductive channel and drain and source regions.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The electrons which comprise the channel are free to move out of the channel through the depletion region if attracted to the drain by drain-to-source voltage.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The depletion region is free of carriers and has a resistance similar to silicon.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Any increase of the drain-to-source voltage will increase the distance from drain to the pinch-off point, increasing the resistance of the depletion region in proportion to the drain-to-source voltage applied.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] This proportional change causes the drain-to-source current to remain relatively fixed, independent of changes to the drain-to-source voltage, quite unlike its ohmic behavior in the linear mode of operation.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Thus, in saturation mode, the FET behaves as a constant-current source rather than as a resistor, and can effectively be used as a voltage amplifier.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In this case, the gate-to-source voltage determines the level of constant current through the channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs can be constructed from various semiconductors, out of which silicon is by far the most common.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Most FETs are made by using conventional bulk semiconductor processing techniques, using a single crystal semiconductor wafer as the active region, or channel.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Such FETs are manufactured using a variety of materials such as silicon carbide (SiC), gallium arsenide (GaAs), gallium nitride (GaN), and indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] In June 2011, IBM announced that it had successfully used graphene-based FETs in an integrated circuit.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] These transistors are capable of about 2.23 GHz cutoff frequency, much higher than standard silicon FETs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The channel of a FET is doped to produce either an n-type semiconductor or a p-type semiconductor.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The drain and source may be doped of opposite type to the channel, in the case of enhancement mode FETs, or doped of similar type to the channel as in depletion mode FETs.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Field-effect transistors are also distinguished by the method of insulation between channel and gate.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Field-effect transistors have high gate-to-drain current resistance, of the order of 100 MΩ or more, providing a high degree of isolation between control and flow.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Because base current noise will increase with shaping time, a FET typically produces less noise than a bipolar junction transistor (BJT), and is found in noise-sensitive electronics such as tuners and low-noise amplifiers for VHF and satellite receivers.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] It exhibits no offset voltage at zero drain current and makes an excellent signal chopper.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] It typically has better thermal stability than a BJT.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Because the FETs are controlled by gate charge, once the gate is closed or open, there is no additional power draw, as there would be with a bipolar junction transistor or with non-latching relays in some states.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] This allows extremely low-power switching, which in turn allows greater miniaturization of circuits because heat dissipation needs are reduced compared to other types of switches.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] A field-effect transistor has a relatively low gain–bandwidth product compared to a bipolar junction transistor.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] MOSFETs are very susceptible to overload voltages, thus requiring special handling during installation.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] The thin insulating layer of the MOSFET between the gate and the channel makes it vulnerable to electrostatic discharge or changes to threshold voltage during handling.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] This is not usually a problem after the device has been installed in a properly designed circuit.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FETs often have a very low "on" resistance and have a high "off" resistance.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] However, the intermediate resistances are significant, and so FETs can dissipate large amounts of power while switching.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Thus, efficiency can put a premium on switching quickly, but this can cause transients that can excite stray inductances and generate significant voltages that can couple to the gate and cause unintentional switching.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] FET circuits can therefore require very careful layout and can involve trades between switching speed and power dissipation.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] There is also a trade-off between voltage rating and "on" resistance, so high-voltage FETs have a relatively high "on" resistance and hence conduction losses.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Field-effect transistors are relatively robust, especially when operated within the temperature and electrical limitations defined by the manufacturer (proper derating).
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] However, modern FET devices can often incorporate a body diode.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] If the characteristics of the body diode are not taken into consideration, the FET can experience slow body diode behavior, where a parasitic transistor will turn on and allow high current to be drawn from drain to source when the FET is off.
[src:carbon-nanotubes/field-effect-transistor] Source-gated transistors are more robust to manufacturing and environmental issues in large-area electronics such as display screens, but are slower in operation than FETs.
